  "exemplar_id": "ex_biliary_colic_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Adult female presenting with several days of sharp right upper quadrant abdominal pain that has acutely worsened over the last 3-4 hours, now rated 8/10. The pain is non-radiating, associated with nausea but no vomiting, and unrelieved by Tylenol and Advil. She has been told to lose weight, occasionally uses antacids for heartburn, drinks 1-2 glasses of wine nightly, and her mother has gallstones. She mentioned a similar but milder episode a few years ago that self-resolved. The doctor is probing what was happening when the pain initially started three days ago.",
  "good_next_question": "What were you doing right prior to the pain starting?",
  "rationale": "This open-but-targeted question tests the classic biliary colic trigger pattern — pain onset 30-60 minutes after a meal, especially a fatty one — which the patient indeed confirms ('after lunch around half an hour or an hour after'). In a patient who already fits the 'female, forty-ish, family history of stones, overweight' profile, postprandial timing is the feature that distinguishes biliary colic from peptic ulcer disease (often relieved by food), pancreatitis (pain typically constant and bores through to the back), hepatitis (no relation to meals), or MSK pain. A positive answer locks in gallstone disease as the working diagnosis and reorders the workup toward RUQ ultrasound plus LFTs/lipase to assess for choledocholithiasis or cholecystitis. Asking about prior activity beats asking about pain quality again because timing relative to eating is more discriminating than character at this point — sharp RUQ pain has many causes, but sharp postprandial RUQ pain narrows the field dramatically.",
  "tags": [
    "abdominal_pain",
    "gastrointestinal",
    "biliary",
    "differential_completion",
    "timeline",
    "risk_factor_probe"
  ],
